sec.p:
Tancoš et al. (2023) proposed two sets of models relating to fluid intelligence in children: first, a model focused on the F > C phenomenon, which controls for item difficulty ( b_i bi) and respondent ability ( \theta_j θj) with an added interaction term of answer correctness ( FC_{ij} FCij) and respondent ability. This model is given by (Tancoš et al., 2023, p. 7): \ln{(t_{ij})}=\mu+\nu_j+\beta_i+\gamma_1 FC_{ij}+\gamma_2 b_i+\gamma_3 \theta_j+\gamma_{13} FC_{ij}\theta_j+\epsilon_{ij}, ln(tij)=μ+νj+βi+γ1FCij+γ2bi+γ3θj+γ13FCijθj+ϵij, where \ln{t_{ij}} lntij is a logarithmic transformation of the response time for person
j j on item i i;
\mu μ is the fixed intercept (representing the time spent by an average-ability respondent on an average-difficulty item);
\nu_j νj is the random intercept for each person (general speediness of respondent j j; the average time respondent j j spent across all items); \beta_i βi is the random intercept for each item (time required by a person of average ability to answer item i i);
\gamma_1 γ1,
\gamma_2 γ2,
\gamma_3 γ3, and \gamma_{13} γ13 are the fixed effects of the corresponding predictors; and
\epsilon_{ij} ϵij is the normally distributed residual.

The second model Tancoš et al. (2023) proposed assesses the distance-difficulty hypothesis and investigates its incremental validity over the F > C phenomenon. This model is represented by (Tancoš et al., 2023, p. 8): \ln{(t_{ij})}=\mu+\nu_j+\beta_i+\gamma_4 \delta_{ij}+\gamma_1 FC_{ij}+\gamma_14 FC_{ij} \delta_{ij}+\epsilon_{ij}, ln(tij)=μ+νj+βi+γ4δij+γ1FCij+γ14FCijδij+ϵij, where \ln{(t_{ij})} ln(tij) is a logarithmic transformation of the response time for person
j j on item i i;
\mu μ is the fixed intercept; \nu_j νj is the random intercept for each person;
\beta_i βi is the random intercept for each item;
\delta_{ij}=|\theta_j-b_i| δij=|θj−bi| is the absolute distance between respondent
j j’s ability level and item i i’s difficulty; FC_{ij} FCij is a binary variable representing item correctness;
\gamma_1 γ1,
\gamma_2 γ2,
\gamma_3 γ3, and \gamma_{13} γ13 are the fixed effects of the corresponding predictors; and
\epsilon_{ij} ϵij is the normally distributed residual.
